Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The list of countries demonstrating poliovirus circulation (WPV or cVDPV) in the past 2 months through isolation of the virus from cases of AFP (acute flaccid paralysis), from healthy community contacts of cases of AFP, or from environmental sampling keeps growing, with Benin joining the list of countries with cVDPVs.

It is unclear whether there have been 15 or 16 cases reported from Nigeria during 2019, albeit the grand total of 51 cVDPV cases reported during 2019 is consistent with 16 total cases reported from Nigeria. Also it is unclear if the genetic studies of the cVDPV2 identified in Benin is related to one of the outbreaks ongoing in Nigeria.

If one looks at a map of Africa, one is struck by the current "clusters" of countries reporting cVDPVs. In West Africa, Nigeria has 2 or 3 independent outbreaks of cVDPV2, and all 3 neighboring countries sharing a border with Nigeria (Benin, Cameroon and Niger) plus Ghana (which is on the western side of Togo, which shares its eastern border with Benin) have reported cases. Then there is the DRC, which shares borders with the Central African Republic (which also shares a border with Cameroon) and Angola. The next cluster is in Eastern Africa with Somalia sharing borders with Kenya and Ethiopia. The isolated country as yet not clustered with other countries is Mozambique. A major concern are the other countries making up Western, Central and Eastern Africa that have not as yet reported cases, including those in the Lake Chad region, where vaccination coverages are suboptimal. A question that remains unanswered is whether the use of the mOPV2 (monovalent type 2 oral polio vaccine) is the way to permanently interrupt cVDPV2 transmission in an area with challenges in routine vaccination coverages or whether its use (and subsequent flooding such an area with the OPV2 virus) creates a vicious circle.

As done in previous posts, to visualize all of this activity, I am putting links to HealthMap/ProMED-mail maps of countries with poliovirus activity during the past 12 months below. The size of the list remains impressive now with 19 countries -- 12 in Africa, 5 in Asia, and 2 in the Western Pacific.

